{"parse":{"title":"Crown of justification","pageid":39073905,"revid":632765650,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Fayum-80.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Fayum-80.jpg/170px-Fayum-80.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"358\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Fayum-80.jpg/255px-Fayum-80.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/28/Fayum-80.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"304\" data-file-height=\"640\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Fayum-80.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Fayum_mummy_portrait\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Fayum mummy portrait\">Fayum mummy portrait</a> showing the deceased wearing a \"crown of justification,\" with the rhombus-shaped leaves representing laurel<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Egyptian_religion\" title=\"Ancient Egyptian religion\">ancient Egyptian religion</a>, the <b>crown of justification</b> <i>(m\u0292\u1e25 n m\u0292\u2018 \u1e2brw</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>) was a <a href=\"/wiki/Wreath\" title=\"Wreath\">wreath</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Fillet_(clothing)\" title=\"Fillet (clothing)\">fillet</a> worn by the deceased to represent victory over death in the <a href=\"/wiki/Egyptian_afterlife\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Egyptian afterlife\">afterlife</a>. Its symbolism is based on Chapter 19 of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Egyptian_Book_of_the_Dead\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Egyptian Book of the Dead\">Book of the Dead</a>,</i> in which the wearer is said to be \"justified\" by a triumph over death just as the god <a href=\"/wiki/Osiris\" title=\"Osiris\">Osiris</a> eventually rose above his enemies. A ritual text was recited as the dead person was crowned.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The crown of justification might be made of laurel, <a href=\"/wiki/Palm_branch_(symbol)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Palm branch (symbol)\">palm</a>, feathers, <a href=\"/wiki/Papyrus\" title=\"Papyrus\">papyrus</a>, or precious metals. It was syncretized with the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_crown\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Solar crown\">solar crown</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun_god\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sun god\">sun god</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Ra\" title=\"Ra\">Re</a>, and might be made of gold to mimic the properties of the sun.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Among the collections of the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Fine_Arts,_Boston\" title=\"Museum of Fine Arts, Boston\">Museum of Fine Arts, Boston</a>, is an intricately woven papyrus wreath with bronze insets to reflect light.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> In the <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Empire\" title=\"Roman Empire\">Roman era</a>, initiates into the <a href=\"/wiki/Mysteries_of_Isis\" title=\"Mysteries of Isis\">mysteries of Isis</a> might wear a wreath of palm leaves to suggest the rays of the sun.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the <a href=\"/wiki/Ptolemaic_Kingdom\" title=\"Ptolemaic Kingdom\">Ptolemaic</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Egypt\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roman Egypt\">Roman Imperial</a> periods, <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Egyptian_art\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ancient Egyptian art\">religious art</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Egyptian_temple\" title=\"Egyptian temple\">temples</a> shows the king offering the crown to <a href=\"/wiki/Horus\" title=\"Horus\">Horus</a> or other <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Egyptian_deities\" title=\"Ancient Egyptian deities\">deities</a>. These crowns of justification take the form of a circlet, which sometimes has a <a href=\"/wiki/Uraeus\" title=\"Uraeus\">uraeus</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Wedjat\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wedjat\">wedjat</a>-eye.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Rosalia_(festival)\" title=\"Rosalia (festival)\">Rose wreaths</a> might be substituted during the Roman period, in reference to the use of rose garlands and wreaths in the <a href=\"/wiki/Interpretatio_graeca\" title=\"Interpretatio graeca\">Romanized</a> mysteries of Isis.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> The crown of justification was in this way integrated into the broader festal and religious uses of floral and vegetative wreaths in the Roman Empire.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crown_of_justification&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Crowns_of_Egypt\" title=\"Crowns of Egypt\">Crowns of Egypt</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Crown_of_Immortality\" title=\"Crown of Immortality\">Crown of Immortality</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crown_of_justification&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Lorelei H. Corcoran and Marie Svoboda, <i>Herakleides: A Portrait Mummy from Roman Egypt</i> (Getty Publications, 2010), p. 32.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Wb.</i> ii. 31. 5.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Christina Riggs, <i>The Beautiful Burial in Roman Egypt: Art, Identity, and Funerary Religion</i> (Oxford University Press, 2005), p. 81.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Corcoran and Svoboda, <i>Herakleides,</i> p. 32.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Fine_Arts,_Boston\" title=\"Museum of Fine Arts, Boston\">Museum of Fine Arts, Boston</a>, inv. 50.3788; Corcoran and Svoboda, <i>Herakleides,</i> pp. 32\u201333.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">As described by <a href=\"/wiki/Apuleius\" title=\"Apuleius\">Apuleius</a>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Golden_Ass\" title=\"The Golden Ass\">Metamorphoses</a></i>; Corcoran and Svoboda, <i>Herakleides,</i> p. 32.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Riggs, <i>The Beautiful Burial in Roman Egypt,</i> p. 81.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Riggs, <i>The Beautiful Burial in Roman Egypt,</i> pp. 81\u201382.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Riggs, <i>The Beautiful Burial in Roman Egypt,</i> pp. 82\u201383.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2272\nCached time: 20180915133549\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.048 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.056 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 186/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 350/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 86/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2759/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.004/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   28.400      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   28.400      1 -total\n 10.31%    2.928      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:39073905-0!canonical and timestamp 20180915133549 and revision id 632765650\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"it","url":"https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corona_di_giustificazione","langname":"Italian","autonym":"italiano","*":"Corona di giustificazione"}],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Crowns_(headgear)"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Ancient_Egyptian_funerary_practices"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ancient Egyptian art"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ancient Egyptian deities"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ancient Egyptian religion"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Apuleius"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Crown of Immortality"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Crowns of Egypt"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Egyptian Book of the Dead"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Egyptian afterlife"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Egyptian temple"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Fayum mummy portrait"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Fillet (clot